Use a symbolic rule engine. Arithmetic constraint satisfaction (CSP) over 100 variables is a well-structured combinatorial problem where symbolic solvers (e.g., Z3, OR-Tools, Choco) provide soundness, completeness, and explainability by construction. Neural approaches lack guaranteed constraint satisfaction, require expensive training data, and generalize poorly to out-of-distribution variable counts or constraint types. 100 variables is well within the practical range of modern SMT/CP solvers — OR-Tools CP-SAT handles millions of variables. Neural modules excel at perception and pattern recognition, not exact logical inference; they approximate solutions and can violate hard constraints silently. For arithmetic constraints specifically (linear, nonlinear, integer), symbolic solvers exploit algebraic structure via propagation, branch-and-bound, and DPLL(T) — techniques with no neural equivalent in reliability. If you need learned heuristics to guide search, a hybrid (neural-guided MCTS or learned variable ordering atop a symbolic solver) is preferable to pure neural. Default to OR-Tools or Z3 unless you have a compelling domain-specific reason otherwise.
